post_text:
Dear Parents and Guardians of our Distance Learning Academy,

Over the course of this week we are collecting the textbooks of our middle school and high school Distance Learning Academy students from their teachers. On Saturday, September 12th, we will be distributing these textbooks to families between 9:00am and 12:00pm. In order to distribute the books in an orderly fashion, we ask that you report to your child‚Äôs school at the following times:

Last Name A - G: 9:00am - 10:00am
Last Name H - P: 10:00am - 11:00am
Last Name Q - Z: 11:00am - 12:00pm

Textbooks for middle school students can be picked up at the entrance near the middle school gymnasium. Textbooks for high school students can be picked up at the entrance near the high school gymnasium.

Please wear a mask and maintain social distancing when coming to our school buildings.

Thank you for your cooperation. We look forward to seeing you on Saturday morning.

Sincerely,

Georgianna Diopolous, WVMS Principal
Marguerite Fusco, WVHS Principal

post_text:
Warwick Valley High School opened its doors at 7:15 this morning to welcome back students in cohort A for the first day of the 2020-21 school year. "We are so excited to start the school year with live instruction in our high school," WVHS Principal Marguerite Fusco said. "Students were wearing big smiles behind their masks as they entered the building. All in all, it was a great day and things went rather smoothly. We are looking forward to meeting the next cohort tomorrow and expect everything to go as well as it did today."
--

üçé üíª Learning is a lifelong thing! üíªüçé

"Warwick Valley teachers are working harder than ever to prepare for the 2020-2021 school year," said Superintendent of Schools Dr. David Leach. "Our new learning model also requires a new paradigm of teaching. Everyone is excited for what September will bring."

Training and development is ongoing at the District Office and throughout the district. Virtual Town Halls with the public begin next week!

"Warwick Valley teachers are working harder than ever to prepare for the 2020-2021 school year," said Superintendent of Schools Dr. David Leach. "Our new learning model also requires a new paradigm of teaching. Everyone is excited for what September will bring."

Training and development is ongoing at the District Office and throughout the district. Virtual Town Halls with the public begin next week!

post_text: The Park Avenue Elementary PTA annual Crazy Ticket fundraiser was scheduled to be held on March 20th in the Park Avenue Gymnasium and was postponed due to the social distancing guidlelines. With some innovative thinking and a dedicated group of parent volunteers, the PTA turned the fundraiser into a virtual, week-long extravaganza. A total of 166 donations and prizes were raffled off, raising over $10,000! These funds will be used toward field trips, enrichment activities and family events over the coming year. The Park Ave PTA is also thrilled to donate $2,500 of these proceeds to Backpack Snack Attack to help provide food for local children in need during this difficult time. The Park Ave PTA would like to especially thank all the local businesses and families who donated items for this event. Your generosity is so appreciated!

Congratulations to the nine Warwick Valley High School teams that are being honored as Winter 2019-20 #NYSPHSAA Scholar-Athlete teams. To qualify as a Scholar-Athlete team, 75% of the team roster‚Äôs averaged GPA must be 90.0 or above. The following Warwick teams met the criteria: boys and girls basketball, boys and girls indoor track and field, boys and girls skiing, boys swimming and diving, and wrestling.

A total of 569 schools across the state participated in the Scholar-Athlete program.

‚ÄúCongratulations to the Scholar-Athlete teams and individuals from the winter 2020 season,‚Äù said Dr. Robert Zayas, NYSPHSAA Executive Director. ‚ÄúThe Scholar-Athlete program continues to be one of the most rewarding endeavors we encourage here at the Association. The winter season was extremely challenging this year, so to see this many student-athletes honored for their work in the classroom is truly rewarding.‚Äù

As a reminder, today is the final day to bid for senior chairs in the annual Chair Auction. The Chair Auction benefits the scholarship fund for WVHS seniors who plan to pursue art in college. For this event, students have taken an ordinary chair, and over the course of several months, transformed it into a work of art. The chairs are auctioned off to the public with 100% of the proceeds going to participating graduating seniors in the form of scholarships.
You can see this year‚Äôs chairs and bid at https://warwickartauction.weebly.com/2020-auction.html

Warwick Valley Coalition
May 31 at 1:29 PM ¬∑

Warwick, NY ‚Äì Did you know 4 out of 5 Warwick students choose not to smoke marijuana? Warwick Valley Prevention Youth Coordinator Francesca Bryson wants to make sure that you do!
The Warwick Valley Prevention Coalition will be initiating a campaign called the Sticker Shock in June. The stickers all have an important message on them taken from the Warwick Youth Survey results of 2019. The sticker shock is designed to be a conversation starter between parents and their children about topics such as drug and alcohol use. We will be distributing the stickers to these locally participating pizzerias: Luca Trattoria- Pizzeria in the Warwick Shoprite Plaza, Frank's Pizza on Main Street, Franico‚Äôs on Elm Street, Franico‚Äôs on Main Street in Florida, and Harvest Luncheonette in Pine Island.

post_text:
School Budget Vote

This year‚Äôs school budget vote and board of education election must take place exclusively by absentee ballot due to the COVID-19 public health crisis. Qualified voters should have now received absentee ballots in the mail. If you are an eligible voter but did NOT receive an absentee ballot, please contact the District Office at 845-987-3000, extension 10511. You may also email slaroe@wvcsd.org.

Please be sure to follow the instructions on your absentee ballot carefully. After marking your ballot, seal it in the oath envelope and place the oath envelope in the postage-paid return envelope addressed to the District Clerk of the Warwick Valley Central School District. Please also date/sign the back of the oath envelope. Absentee ballots must be received by the District Clerk no later than 5 p.m. on the day of the election, June 9, 2020.

Class of 2020! We will light the banners this evening and each evening--Thank you to Brock (Owner of Allied Excavating)for the lights and generator! Again, a big thanks to Eileen Patterson Track 7 Postal Service - incredible job and very generous. Without Eileen Patterson, this project doesn't happen.

And thank you to those who donated money for the metal stakes. The donations break down as follows: Town of Warwick, Village of Warwick, Warwick PBA, and Ed Mullins Minturn Food Truck Park.

Also, thank you to Wadesons' Home Center for your generosity!

Employees from the Town and District -- well done!

Warwick is such a beautiful, caring community.

post_text:
In Mrs. Canfield‚Äôs Park Avenue Elementary School kindergarten class, the children were learning about the Life Cycle of a chicken. Kristina Baumann, Ava and Mason Fury‚Äôs mom, teamed up with Mrs. Canfield to make this experience as memorable as possible. With the help of an incubator and 21 eggs the children were hoping to hatch real chickens in the classroom.

The chickens hatched a few days ago, just not in the classroom.

The first photos were taken on March 11, when the children were introduced to ‚Äúcandling.‚Äù Candling is a method used to study the growth and development of an embryo inside an egg. This method uses a bright light source behind the egg to show details through the shell. The children were amazed that they were able to see the ‚Äúbaby‚Äù through the egg shell.

post_text: At Park Avenue Elementary School last week, fourth grade science class geotechnical engineers are busy analyzing core samples of the Earth and conducting earthquake tests in topsoil, sand, clay and bedrock. The students are working collaboratively to test TarPul models in either rocky or organic soil at three levels of compaction. The results of this test will be a factor to consider in deciding where to construct the TarPul to help the villagers of Nepal cross the Karnali River during monsoon season.

post_text: The Warwick Valley High School robotics club upgraded its robot for the upcoming state competition. The club added an intake system on the back with a 90-degree adjustable ramp that allows the robot to suck up and spit out game elements fast and effectively. They also updated the claw system using linear motion that allows us to reach heights over 36 inches for stacking game elements. The club and their robot will compete at the New York Excelsior FIRST Tech Challenge Championship at SUNY Polytechnic Institute in Utica on March 14th after winning the New York Excelsior Yonkers Qualifier in January.

post_text:
A group of fifth and sixth grade science teachers work with MaryAnne Choma, WVCSD Facilitator for Collaborative Unit Design, to develop units of study that align to the new science learning standards. Each unit of study is expected to have a performance task (performance based learning). The group reviewed
the new learning standards, which are significantly different than the previous standards.

The new standards call for students to shift from "knowing about science" to "knowing and doing" science. Teachers are encouraged to design a performance task that invites the students to dive into the learning.

The teachers also engaged in a formal "feedback round" while they were designing their performance tasks. The feedback round provides each teacher an opportunity to leave their design group and pair with a different teacher. TAfter feedback rounds, the pairs return to their design group, share new ideas, and iterate on the design process for the performance task.

The Florida and Warwick school districts will host a Community Forum for Vaping Awareness at 7 p.m. on Monday, March 2nd at Warwick Valley Middle School. MaryAlice Kovatch, Prevention Coordinator with The Alcoholism and Drug Abuse Council of Orange County, will share significant details about vaping products and the threat they pose to the health of our students.

Over 3,500 youths start vaping every day, according to the American Heart Association. This forum will provide the education and tools necessary to help children avoid the temptation and get the help they need if they are addicted.

Please come out! - 7 p.m., Monday, March 2nd at Warwick Valley Middle School

post_text: Students in Ms. Melican's first grade STEM classes at Park Ave Elementary over the last few weeks have worked on performance tasks for their current STEM-Scopes unit. These performance tasks summarize the learning that's been taking place in the classrooms about light, sound, and communication. In the STEM lab, students work on their mission of creating a device that uses light or sound to communicate over a distance. In partner groups, students make a design plan for the device; then, they create it using various materials. In a presentation, students show the class how the tool works, and evaluate their design using a rubric. As another reflection piece, students record Flipgrid videos, showcasing their device, and explaining their process. By using Flipgrid, students in the class can watch each other's videos, and also provide video comments with compliments and suggestions for improvement.

post_text: Mrs. Leandro facilitated the District Wellness meeting last week. The focus of the meeting was a recap of the Board of Education Work Session held on 1/27/2020, which explored the vaping epidemic faced nationwide as well as the interventions that Warwick has put into place to help with this issue. Associate Principal Chris Radon presented information to the committee and spoke to the specific Middle School programs already in place to help students make safer choices. SADD advisor Kaitlyn Rodriguez also mentioned many of the programs already in place at the High School level as well as activities SADD (Students Against Destructive Decisions) that are in place this year.

post_text: Kindergarten classes celebrated World Read Aloud Day on February 5th, 2020. The kindergarten classes at Park Ave kicked off this exciting day with a special read aloud from Mr. Sibilia in the library. The students were then able to "visit" the different biomes of the world by traveling through each beautifully decorated kindergarten classroom, where they learned fascinating facts about the different parts of the world. The day was celebrated with special guest readers such as Mr. Biniaris, Ms. Faliski, Mr. Sibilla, and kindergarten student readers. The read-alouds focused on different places around the world, such as the rainforest, desert, savannah, arctic, and ocean life, along with what is special about those places. In celebrating this special day we are continuing to foster a love of reading as well as provide some basic knowledge on these different places in order to help the children prepare for an upcoming Stemscopes science unit.
